{"title_page": "BookFinder.com", "text_new": "{{Infobox website\n| name             = BookFinder.com\n| favicon          = \n| logo             = BookFinder.com logo.jpg\n| screenshot       = \n| caption          = \n| url              = https://www.bookfinder.com/\n| commercial       = Yes\n| type             = [[Comparison shopping website]]\n| registration     = \n| programming_language= [[Perl]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robert|first1=Kirrily|title=Site review: BookFinder|url=http://perlbuzz.com/2007/09/site-review-bookfinder.html|website=Perlbuzz|accessdate=14 July 2014|ref=perlbuzz|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023221519/http://perlbuzz.com/2007/09/site-review-bookfinder.html|archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n| owner            = [[AbeBooks]] ([[Amazon (company)|Amazon]])\n| author           = \n| launch_date      = January 30, 1997\n| current_status   = Active\n| revenue          = \n}}\n\n'''BookFinder.com''' is a [[vertical search]] [[website]] that helps readers buy [[books]] online. The site's [[meta-search]] engine scans the [[inventory|inventories]] of over 100,000 booksellers located around the world. Among the books from sellers whose inventories are indexed, users can find the lowest price for a book of their choice from over 150 million volumes available for sale, and purchase titles directly from the bookseller, without a markup.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Maul|first1=Kimberly|title=Bookfinder: Eliminating obscurity|journal=TheBookseller.com|date=March 2, 2007|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/control/?p=18&a=35096|accessdate=14 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080619002723/http://www.thebookseller.com/control/?p=18&a=35096|archivedate=June 19, 2008}}</ref><ref name=about>{{cite web|title=About BookFinder.com|url=http://www.bookfinder.com/about/|website=BookFinder.com|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref> The search engine is focused primarily on [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Italian language|Italian]], and [[Spanish language]] titles.\n\nBookFinder.com was founded in 1997 by Anirvan Chatterjee, then a student at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]; it was one of the earliest vertical search engines for books online.<ref name=\"nyt-19980913\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/09/13/bookend/bookend.html|title = Want to Buy a Rare Book? Click Here.|last = Max|first = D. T.|date = September 13, 1998|work = [[The New York Times]]|accessdate = July 14, 2014}}</ref> Originally known as MX BookFinder,<ref name=\"nyt-19980913\"/> it was relaunched as BookFinder.com in 1998 and established as a standalone company based in [[Berkeley, California]] in 1999.\n\nIn 2005, BookFinder.com was acquired by [[AbeBooks]],<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.internetnews.com/ec-news/article.php/3562321|title = Book Sites Unite|last = Needle|first = David|date = November 7, 2005|work = InternetNews|accessdate = July 14, 2014}}</ref> which itself was purchased by [[Amazon.com]] on August 1, 2008.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Amazon.com Acquires AbeBooks |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=176060&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1231146&highlight= |location=Seattle, Washington & Victoria, British Columbia |publisher=Amazon.com |agency= |date= |accessdate=2014-07-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://techcrunch.com/2008/08/01/amazon-to-acquire-abebooks/ |last=Arrington|first=Michael|work=[[TechCrunch]]|title=Amazon To Acquire AbeBooks, And With It A Stake In LibraryThing}}</ref>\n\nBookFinder.com started operating in Europe under the JustBooks brand in 2006. There are currently JustBooks/BookFinder.com portals for [[France]], [[Germany]], the [[Netherlands]], and the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"about\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news |first=Michelle |last=Slatalla |title=Knowledge Is Priceless but Textbooks Are Not |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/30/fashion/30Cyber.html |work=The New York Times |date=2007-08-30 |accessdate=2007-10-30 }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.bookfinder.com/}}\n\n{{Amazon}}\n\n[[Category:Book websites]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Product searching websites]]\n[[Category:Online marketplaces of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox website\n| name             = BookFinder.com\n| favicon          = \n| logo             = BookFinder.com logo.jpg\n| screenshot       = \n| caption          = \n| url              = https://www.bookfinder.com/\n| commercial       = Yes\n| type             = [[Comparison shopping website]]\n| registration     = \n| programming_language= [[Perl]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robert|first1=Kirrily|title=Site review: BookFinder|url=http://perlbuzz.com/2007/09/site-review-bookfinder.html|website=Perlbuzz|accessdate=14 July 2014|ref=perlbuzz|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141023221519/http://perlbuzz.com/2007/09/site-review-bookfinder.html|archivedate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n| owner            = [[AbeBooks]] ([[Amazon (company)|Amazon]])\n| author           = \n| launch_date      = January 30, 1997\n| current_status   = Active\n| revenue          = \n}}\n\n'''BookFinder.com''' is a [[vertical search]] [[website]] that helps readers buy [[books]] online. The site's [[meta-search]] engine scans the inventories of over 100,000 booksellers located around the world. Among the books from sellers whose inventories are indexed, users can find the lowest price for a book of their choice from over 150 million volumes available for sale, and purchase titles directly from the bookseller, without a markup.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Maul|first1=Kimberly|title=Bookfinder: Eliminating obscurity|journal=TheBookseller.com|date=March 2, 2007|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/control/?p=18&a=35096|accessdate=14 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080619002723/http://www.thebookseller.com/control/?p=18&a=35096|archivedate=June 19, 2008}}</ref><ref name=about>{{cite web|title=About BookFinder.com|url=http://www.bookfinder.com/about/|website=BookFinder.com|accessdate=14 July 2014}}</ref> The search engine is focused primarily on [[Dutch language|Dutch]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[German language|German]], [[Italian language|Italian]], and [[Spanish language]] titles.\n\nBookFinder.com was founded in 1997 by Anirvan Chatterjee, then a student at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]; it was one of the earliest vertical search engines for books online.<ref name=\"nyt-19980913\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.nytimes.com/books/98/09/13/bookend/bookend.html|title = Want to Buy a Rare Book? Click Here.|last = Max|first = D. T.|date = September 13, 1998|work = [[The New York Times]]|accessdate = July 14, 2014}}</ref> Originally known as MX BookFinder,<ref name=\"nyt-19980913\"/> it was relaunched as BookFinder.com in 1998 and established as a standalone company based in [[Berkeley, California]] in 1999.\n\nIn 2005, BookFinder.com was acquired by [[AbeBooks]],<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.internetnews.com/ec-news/article.php/3562321|title = Book Sites Unite|last = Needle|first = David|date = November 7, 2005|work = InternetNews|accessdate = July 14, 2014}}</ref> which itself was purchased by [[Amazon.com]] on August 1, 2008.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Amazon.com Acquires AbeBooks |url=http://phx.corporate-ir.net/phoenix.zhtml?c=176060&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=1231146&highlight= |location=Seattle, Washington & Victoria, British Columbia |publisher=Amazon.com |agency= |date= |accessdate=2014-07-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://techcrunch.com/2008/08/01/amazon-to-acquire-abebooks/ |last=Arrington|first=Michael|work=[[TechCrunch]]|title=Amazon To Acquire AbeBooks, And With It A Stake In LibraryThing}}</ref>\n\nBookFinder.com started operating in Europe under the JustBooks brand in 2006. There are currently JustBooks/BookFinder.com portals for [[France]], [[Germany]], the [[Netherlands]], and the [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref name=\"about\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news |first=Michelle |last=Slatalla |title=Knowledge Is Priceless but Textbooks Are Not |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/08/30/fashion/30Cyber.html |work=The New York Times |date=2007-08-30 |accessdate=2007-10-30 }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.bookfinder.com/}}\n\n{{Amazon}}\n\n[[Category:Book websites]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1999]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Product searching websites]]\n[[Category:Online marketplaces of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Nasd7d", "label": "safe", "comment": "added a wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BookFinder.com"}
{"title_page": "Rhombicosidodecahedron", "text_new": "{{Semireg polyhedra db|Semireg polyhedron stat table|lrID}}\n[[File:Rhombicosidodecahedron.stl|thumb|3D model of a rhombicosidodecahedron]]\nIn [[geometry]], the '''rhombicosidodecahedron''', is an [[Archimedean solid]], one of thirteen [[Convex polytope|convex]] [[Isogonal figure|isogonal]] nonprismatic solids constructed of two or more types of [[regular polygon]] [[Face (geometry)|face]]s.\n\nIt has 20 regular [[triangular]] faces, 30 [[square (geometry)|square]] faces, 12 regular [[pentagon]]al faces, 60 [[vertex (geometry)|vertices]], and 120 [[edge (geometry)|edges]].\n\n==Names==\n{{multiple image\n | align = left  | total_width = 400\n | image1 = Nonuniform rhombicosidodecahedron as rectified rhombic triacontahedron max.png\n | image2 = Rhombicosidodecahedron in rhombic triacontahedron max.png\n | image3 = Nonuniform rhombicosidodecahedron as core of dual compound max.png\n}}\n[[Johannes Kepler]] in [[Harmonices Mundi]] (1618) named this polyhedron a ''rhombicosidodecahedron'', being short for ''truncated icosidodecahedral rhombus'', with ''icosidodecahedral rhombus'' being his name for a [[rhombic triacontahedron]].<ref>''Harmonies Of The World'' by Johannes Kepler, Translated into English with an introduction and notes by ''E. J. Aiton'', ''A. M. Duncan'', \"J. V. Field'', 1997, {{isbn|0-87169-209-0}} (page 123)</ref> There are different truncations of a rhombic triacontahedron into a [[topology|topological]] rhombicosidodecahedron: Prominently its [[rectification (geometry)|rectification]] (left), the one that creates the uniform solid (center), and the rectification of the dual [[icosidodecahedron]] (right), which is the core of the [[dual compound]].\n\nIt can also be called an ''[[Expansion (geometry)|expanded]]'' or ''[[Cantellation (geometry)|cantellated]]'' dodecahedron or icosahedron, from truncation operations on either [[uniform polyhedron]].\n\n==Geometric relations==\nIf you [[Expansion (geometry)|expand]] an [[icosahedron]] by moving the faces away from the [[Origin (mathematics)|origin]] the right amount, without changing the orientation or size of the faces, and do the same to its [[dual polyhedron|dual]] [[dodecahedron]], and patch the square holes in the result, you get a rhombicosidodecahedron. Therefore, it has the same number of triangles as an icosahedron and the same number of pentagons as a dodecahedron, with a square for each edge of either.\n\nAlternatively, if you [[Expansion (geometry)|expand]] each of five cubes by moving the faces away from the [[Origin (mathematics)|origin]] the right amount and rotating each of the five 72\u00b0 around so they are equidisant from each other, without changing the orientation or size of the faces, and patch the pentagonal and triangular holes in the result, you get a rhombicosidodecahedron. Therefore, it has the same number of triangles as an icosahedron and the same number of pentagons as a dodecahedron, with a square for each edge of either.\n\nThe rhombicosidodecahedron shares the vertex arrangement with the [[small stellated truncated dodecahedron]], and with the uniform compounds of six or twelve [[pentagrammic prism]]s.\n\nThe [[Zometool]] kits for making [[geodesic dome]]s and other polyhedra use slotted balls as connectors. The balls are \"expanded\" rhombicosidodecahedra, with the squares replaced by rectangles. The expansion is chosen so that the resulting rectangles are [[golden rectangle]]s.\n\nTwelve of the 92 [[Johnson solid]]s are derived from the rhombicosidodecahedron, four of them by rotation of one or more [[pentagonal cupola]]e: the [[gyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|gyrate]], [[parabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|parabigyrate]], [[metabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|metabigyrate]], and [[trigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron]]. Eight more can be constructed by removing up to three cupolae, sometimes also rotating one or more of the other cupolae.\n\n==Cartesian coordinates==\n[[Cartesian coordinates]] for the vertices of a rhombicosidodecahedron with an edge length of 2 centered at the origin are all [[even permutation]]s of:<ref>{{mathworld |title=Icosahedral group |urlname=IcosahedralGroup}}</ref>\n:(\u00b11, \u00b11, \u00b1''\u03c6''<sup>3</sup>),\n:(\u00b1''\u03c6''<sup>2</sup>, \u00b1''\u03c6'', \u00b12''\u03c6''),\n:(\u00b1(2+''\u03c6''), 0, \u00b1''\u03c6''<sup>2</sup>),\nwhere ''\u03c6''&nbsp;=&nbsp;{{sfrac|1 + {{sqrt|5}}|2}} is the [[golden ratio]]. Therefore, the circumradius of this rhombicosidodecahedron is the common distance of these points from the origin, namely {{sqrt|''\u03c6''<sup>6</sup>+2}} = {{sqrt|''8\u03c6+7''}} for edge length 2. For unit edge length, R must be halved, giving \n:''R'' = {{sfrac|{{sqrt|8''\u03c6''+7}}|2}} = {{sfrac|{{sqrt|11+4{{sqrt|5}}}}|2}} &asymp; 2.233.\n\n==Orthogonal projections==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right | perrow = 1 | total_width = 200\n | image1 = Houghton Typ 520.43.454, crop solid and owl.jpg\n | image2 = Fotothek df tg 0003625, crop rhombicosidodecahedron.jpg\n | footer = Orthogonal projections in ''Geometria'' (1543) by [[Augustin Hirschvogel]]\n}}\nThe ''rhombicosidodecahedron'' has six special [[orthogonal projection]]s, centered, on a vertex, on two types of edges, and three types of faces: triangles, squares, and pentagons. The last two correspond to the A<sub>2</sub> and H<sub>2</sub> [[Coxeter plane]]s.\n{|class=wikitable width=640\n|+ Orthogonal projections\n|-\n!Centered by\n!Vertex\n!Edge<br>3-4\n!Edge<br>5-4\n!Face<br>Square\n!Face<br>Triangle\n!Face<br>Pentagon\n|-\n!Solid\n|\n|\n|\n|[[File:Polyhedron small rhombi 12-20 from blue max.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Polyhedron small rhombi 12-20 from yellow max.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Polyhedron small rhombi 12-20 from red max.png|100px]]\n|-\n!Wireframe\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 v.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 e34.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 e45.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 f4.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 A2.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 H3.png|100px]]\n|- align=center\n!Projective<BR>symmetry\n|[2]\n|[2]\n|[2]\n|[2]\n|[6]\n|[10]\n|-\n!Dual<BR>image\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 v.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 e34.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 e45.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 f4.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 A2.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 H3.png|100px]]\n|}\n\n==Spherical tiling==\nThe rhombicosidodecahedron can also be represented as a [[spherical tiling]], and projected onto the plane via a [[stereographic projection]]. This projection is [[Conformal map|conformal]], preserving angles but not areas or lengths. Straight lines on the sphere are projected as circular arcs on the plane.\n{|class=wikitable\n|- align=center valign=top\n|[[Image:Uniform tiling 532-t02.png|160px]]\n|[[Image:rhombicosidodecahedron stereographic projection pentagon'.png|160px]]<br>[[Pentagon]]-centered\n|[[Image:rhombicosidodecahedron stereographic projection triangle.png|160px]]<br>[[Triangle]]-centered\n|[[Image:rhombicosidodecahedron stereographic projection square.png|160px]]<br>[[Square]]-centered\n|-\n![[Orthographic projection]]\n!colspan=3|[[Stereographic projection]]s\n|}\n\n==Related polyhedra==\n[[File:P4-A11-P5.gif|thumb|[[Expansion (geometry)|Expansion]] of either a [[dodecahedron]] or an [[icosahedron]] creates a rhombicosidodecahedron.]]\n[[File:Zome vertices.jpg|thumb|160px|A version with golden rectangles is used as vertex element of the [[construction set]] [[Zometool]].<ref>{{mathworld |title=Zome|urlname=Zome}}</ref>]]\n\n{{Icosahedral truncations}}\n\n=== Symmetry mutations===\nThis polyhedron is topologically related as a part of a sequence of [[Cantellation (geometry)|cantellated]] polyhedra with vertex figure (3.4.n.4), which continues as tilings of the [[Hyperbolic space|hyperbolic plane]]. These [[vertex-transitive]] figures have (*n32) reflectional [[Orbifold notation|symmetry]].\n\n{{Expanded small table}}\n\n===Johnson solids===\nThere are 13 related [[Johnson solid]]s, 5 by diminishment, and 8 including gyrations:\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ Diminished\n|- align=center\n| [[Pentagonal cupola|J5]]<BR>[[Image:Pentagonal cupola.png|100px]]\n| [[Diminished rhombicosidodecahedron|76]]<BR>[[Image:Diminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Parabidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron|80]]<BR>[[Image:Parabidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Metabidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron|81]]<BR>[[Image:Metabidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Tridiminished rhombicosidodecahedron|83]]<BR>[[Image:Tridiminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n|}\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ Gyrated and/or diminished\n|- align=center\n| [[Gyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|72]]<BR>[[Image:Gyrate rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Parabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|73]]<BR>[[Image:Parabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Metabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|74]]<BR>[[Image:Metabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Trigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|75]]<BR>[[Image:Trigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n|- align=center\n| [[Paragyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron|77]]<BR>[[Image:Paragyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Metagyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron|78]]<BR>[[Image:Metagyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Bigyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron|79]]<BR>[[Image:Bigyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Gyrate bidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron|82]]<BR>[[Image:Gyrate bidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Vertex arrangement===\nThe rhombicosidodecahedron shares its [[vertex arrangement]] with three [[nonconvex uniform polyhedra]]: the [[small stellated truncated dodecahedron]], the [[small dodecicosidodecahedron]] (having the triangular and pentagonal faces in common), and the [[small rhombidodecahedron]] (having the square faces in common).\n\nIt also shares its vertex arrangement with the [[Polyhedron compound#Uniform compounds|uniform compounds]] of [[compound of six pentagrammic prisms|six]] or [[compound of twelve pentagrammic prisms|twelve pentagrammic prisms]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:400px; vertical-align:top; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|[[File:Small rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]<br>'''Rhombicosidodecahedron'''\n|[[File:Small dodecicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]<br>[[Small dodecicosidodecahedron]]\n|[[File:Small rhombidodecahedron.png|100px]]<br>[[Small rhombidodecahedron]]\n|-\n|[[File:Small stellated truncated dodecahedron.png|100px]]<br>[[Small stellated truncated dodecahedron]]\n|[[File:UC36-6 pentagrammic prisms.png|100px]]<br>[[Compound of six pentagrammic prisms]]\n|[[File:UC37-12 pentagrammic prisms.png|100px]]<br>[[Compound of twelve pentagrammic prisms]]\n|}\n\n== Rhombicosidodecahedral graph ==\n{{Infobox graph\n | name = Rhombicosidodecahedral graph\n | image = [[File:Rhombicosidodecahedral graph.png|240px]]\n | image_caption = Pentagon centered Schlegel diagram\n | namesake = \n | vertices = 60\n | edges = 120\n | automorphisms = 120\n | radius = \n | diameter = \n | girth = \n | chromatic_number =\n | chromatic_index = \n | fractional_chromatic_index = \n | properties = [[Quartic graph]], [[hamiltonian graph|Hamiltonian]], [[regular graph|regular]]\n}}\nIn the [[mathematics|mathematical]] field of [[graph theory]], a '''rhombicosidodecahedral graph''' is the [[1-skeleton|graph of vertices and edges]] of the rhombicosidodecahedron, one of the [[Archimedean solid]]s. It has 60 [[Vertex (graph theory)|vertices]] and 120 edges, and is a [[quartic graph]] [[Archimedean graph]].<ref>{{citation|last1=Read|first1=R. C.|last2=Wilson|first2=R. J.|title=An Atlas of Graphs|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year= 1998|page=269}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rhombicosidodecahedral_graph-squarecenter.png|thumb|left|Square centered [[Schlegel diagram]]]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Truncated rhombicosidodecahedron]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{The Geometrical Foundation of Natural Structure (book)}} (Section 3-9)\n*{{cite book|author=Cromwell, P.|year=1997|title=Polyhedra|location=United Kingdom|publisher=Cambridge|pages=79\u201386 ''Archimedean solids''|isbn=0-521-55432-2}}\n*''[[The Big Bang Theory]] Series 8 Episode 2 - The Junior Professor Solution'': features this solid as the answer to an impromptu science quiz the main four characters have in Leonard and Sheldon's apartment, and is also illustrated in [[Chuck Lorre]]'s '''Vanity Card #461''' at the end of that episode.\n\n==External links==\n*{{mathworld2 |urlname=SmallRhombicosidodecahedron |title=Small Rhombicosidodecahedron |urlname2=ArchimedeanSolid |title2=Archimedean solid}}\n**{{mathworld |urlname=SmallRhombicosidodecahedralGraph |title=Small rhombicosidodecahedron graph}}\n*{{KlitzingPolytopes|polyhedra.htm|3D convex uniform polyhedra|x3o5x - srid}}\n*[http://www.dr-mikes-math-games-for-kids.com/polyhedral-nets.html?&name=Rhombicosidodecahedron#applet Editable printable net of a Rhombicosidodecahedron with interactive 3D view]\n*[http://www.mathconsult.ch/showroom/unipoly/ The Uniform Polyhedra]\n*[http://www.georgehart.com/virtual-polyhedra/vp.html Virtual Reality Polyhedra] The Encyclopedia of Polyhedra\n\n\n{{Archimedean solids}}\n{{Polyhedron navigator}}\n\n[[Category:Uniform polyhedra]]\n[[Category:Archimedean solids]]\n", "text_old": "{{Semireg polyhedra db|Semireg polyhedron stat table|lrID}}\n[[File:Rhombicosidodecahedron.stl|thumb|3D model of a rhombicosidodecahedron]]\nIn [[geometry]], the '''rhombicosidodecahedron''', is an [[Archimedean solid]], one of thirteen [[Convex polytope|convex]] [[Isogonal figure|isogonal]] nonprismatic solids constructed of two or more types of [[regular polygon]] [[Face (geometry)|face]]s.\n\nIt has 20 regular [[triangular]] faces, 30 [[square (geometry)|square]] faces, 12 regular [[pentagon]]al faces, 60 [[vertex (geometry)|vertices]], and 120 [[edge (geometry)|edges]].\n\n==Names==\n{{multiple image\n | align = left  | total_width = 400\n | image1 = Nonuniform rhombicosidodecahedron as rectified rhombic triacontahedron max.png\n | image2 = Rhombicosidodecahedron in rhombic triacontahedron max.png\n | image3 = Nonuniform rhombicosidodecahedron as core of dual compound max.png\n}}\n[[Johannes Kepler]] in [[Harmonices Mundi]] (1618) named this polyhedron a ''rhombicosidodecahedron'', being short for ''truncated icosidodecahedral rhombus'', with ''icosidodecahedral rhombus'' being his name for a [[rhombic triacontahedron]].<ref>''Harmonies Of The World'' by Johannes Kepler, Translated into English with an introduction and notes by ''E. J. Aiton'', ''A. M. Duncan'', \"J. V. Field'', 1997, {{isbn|0-87169-209-0}} (page 123)</ref> There are different truncations of a rhombic triacontahedron into a [[topology|topological]] rhombicosidodecahedron: Prominently its [[rectification (geometry)|rectification]] (left), the one that creates the uniform solid (center), and the rectification of the dual [[icosidodecahedron]] (right), which is the core of the [[dual compound]].\n\nIt can also be called an ''[[Expansion (geometry)|expanded]]'' or ''[[Cantellation (geometry)|cantellated]]'' dodecahedron or icosahedron, from truncation operations on either [[uniform polyhedron]].\n\n==Geometric relations==\nIf you [[Expansion (geometry)|expand]] an [[icosahedron]] by moving the faces away from the [[Origin (mathematics)|origin]] the right amount, without changing the orientation or size of the faces, and do the same to its [[dual polyhedron|dual]] [[dodecahedron]], and patch the square holes in the result, you get a rhombicosidodecahedron. Therefore, it has the same number of triangles as an icosahedron and the same number of pentagons as a dodecahedron, with a square for each edge of either.\n\nAlternatively, if you [[Expansion (geometry)|expand]] each of five cubes by moving the faces away from the [[Origin (mathematics)|origin]] the right amount and rotating each of the five 72\u00b0 around so they are equidisant from each other, without changing the orientation or size of the faces, and patch the pentagonal and triangular holes in the result, you get a rhombicosidodecahedron. Therefore, it has the same number of triangles as an icosahedron and the same number of pentagons as a dodecahedron, with a square for each edge of either.\n\nThe rhombicosidodecahedron shares the vertex arrangement with the [[small stellated truncated dodecahedron]], and with the uniform compounds of six or twelve [[pentagrammic prism]]s.\n\nThe [[Zometool]] kits for making [[geodesic dome]]s and other polyhedra use slotted balls as connectors. The balls are \"expanded\" rhombicosidodecahedra, with the squares replaced by rectangles. The expansion is chosen so that the resulting rectangles are [[golden rectangle]]s.\n\nTwelve of the 92 [[Johnson solid]]s are derived from the rhombicosidodecahedron, four of them by rotation of one or more [[pentagonal cupola]]e: the [[gyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|gyrate]], [[parabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|parabigyrate]], [[metabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|metabigyrate]], and [[trigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron]]. Eight more can be constructed by removing up to three cupolae, sometimes also rotating one or more of the other cupolae.\n\n==Cartesian coordinates==\n[[Cartesian coordinates]] for the vertices of a rhombicosidodecahedron with an edge length of 2 centered at the origin are all [[even permutation]]s of:<ref>{{mathworld |title=Icosahedral group |urlname=IcosahedralGroup}}</ref>\n:(\u00b11, \u00b11, \u00b1''\u03c6''<sup>3</sup>),\n:(\u00b1''\u03c6''<sup>2</sup>, \u00b1''\u03c6'', \u00b12''\u03c6''),\n:(\u00b1(2+''\u03c6''), 0, \u00b1''\u03c6''<sup>2</sup>),\nwhere ''\u03c6''&nbsp;=&nbsp;{{sfrac|1 + {{sqrt|5}}|2}} is the [[golden ratio]]. Therefore, the circumradius of this rhombicosidodecahedron is the common distance of these points from the origin, namely {{sqrt|''\u03c6''<sup>6</sup>+2}} = {{sqrt|''8\u03c6+7''}} for edge length 2. For unit edge length, R must be halved, giving \n:''R'' = {{sfrac|{{sqrt|8''\u03c6''+7}}|2}} = {{sfrac|{{sqrt|11+4{{sqrt|5}}}}|2}} &asymp; 2.233.\n\n==Orthogonal projections==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right | perrow = 1 | total_width = 200\n | image1 = Houghton Typ 520.43.454, crop solid and owl.jpg\n | image2 = Fotothek df tg 0003625, crop rhombicosidodecahedron.jpg\n | footer = Orthogonal projections in ''Geometria'' (1543) by [[Augustin Hirschvogel]]\n}}\nThe ''rhombicosidodecahedron'' has six special [[orthogonal projection]]s, centered, on a vertex, on two types of edges, and three types of faces: triangles, squares, and pentagons. The last two correspond to the A<sub>2</sub> and H<sub>2</sub> [[Coxeter plane]]s.\n{|class=wikitable width=640\n|+ Orthogonal projections\n|-\n!Centered by\n!Vertex\n!Edge<br>3-4\n!Edge<br>5-4\n!Face<br>Square\n!Face<br>Triangle\n!Face<br>Pentagon\n|-\n!Solid\n|\n|\n|\n|[[File:Polyhedron small rhombi 12-20 from blue max.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Polyhedron small rhombi 12-20 from yellow max.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Polyhedron small rhombi 12-20 from red max.png|100px]]\n|-\n!Wireframe\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 v.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 e34.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 e45.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 f4.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 A2.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dodecahedron t02 H3.png|100px]]\n|- align=center\n!Projective<BR>symmetry\n|[2]\n|[2]\n|[2]\n|[2]\n|[6]\n|[10]\n|-\n!Dual<BR>image\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 v.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 e34.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 e45.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 f4.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 A2.png|100px]]\n|[[File:Dual dodecahedron t02 H3.png|100px]]\n|}\n\n==Spherical tiling==\nThe rhombicosidodecahedron can also be represented as a [[spherical tiling]], and projected onto the plane via a [[stereographic projection]]. This projection is [[Conformal map|conformal]], preserving angles but not areas or lengths. Straight lines on the sphere are projected as circular arcs on the plane.\n{|class=wikitable\n|- align=center valign=top\n|[[Image:Uniform tiling 532-t02.png|160px]]\n|[[Image:rhombicosidodecahedron stereographic projection pentagon'.png|160px]]<br>[[Pentagon]]-centered\n|[[Image:rhombicosidodecahedron stereographic projection triangle.png|160px]]<br>[[Triangle]]-centered\n|[[Image:rhombicosidodecahedron stereographic projection square.png|160px]]<br>[[Square]]-centered\n|-\n![[Orthographic projection]]\n!colspan=3|[[Stereographic projection]]s\n|}\n\n==Related polyhedra==\n[[File:P4-A11-P5.gif|thumb|[[Expansion (geometry)|Expansion]] of either a [[dodecahedron]] or an [[icosahedron]] creates a rhombicosidodecahedron.]]\n[[File:Zome vertices.jpg|thumb|160px|A version with golden rectangles is used as vertex element of the [[construction set]] [[Zometool]].<ref>{{mathworld |title=Zome|urlname=Zome}}</ref>]]\n\n{{Icosahedral truncations}}\n\n=== Symmetry mutations===\nThis polyhedron is topologically related as a part of a sequence of [[Cantellation (geometry)|cantellated]] polyhedra with vertex figure (3.4.n.4), which continues as tilings of the [[Hyperbolic space|hyperbolic plane]]. These [[vertex-transitive]] figures have (*n32) reflectional [[Orbifold notation|symmetry]].\n\n{{Expanded small table}}\n\n===Johnson solids===\nThere are 13 related [[Johnson solid]]s, 5 by diminishment, and 8 including gyrations:\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ Diminished\n|- align=center\n| [[Pentagonal cupola|J5]]<BR>[[Image:Pentagonal cupola.png|100px]]\n| [[Diminished rhombicosidodecahedron|76]]<BR>[[Image:Diminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Parabidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron|80]]<BR>[[Image:Parabidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Metabidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron|81]]<BR>[[Image:Metabidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Tridiminished rhombicosidodecahedron|83]]<BR>[[Image:Tridiminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n|}\n{| class=wikitable\n|+ Gyrated and/or diminished\n|- align=center\n| [[Gyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|72]]<BR>[[Image:Gyrate rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Parabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|73]]<BR>[[Image:Parabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Metabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|74]]<BR>[[Image:Metabigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Trigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron|75]]<BR>[[Image:Trigyrate rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n|- align=center\n| [[Paragyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron|77]]<BR>[[Image:Paragyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Metagyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron|78]]<BR>[[Image:Metagyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Bigyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron|79]]<BR>[[Image:Bigyrate diminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n| [[Gyrate bidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron|82]]<BR>[[Image:Gyrate bidiminished rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]\n|}\n\n===Vertex arrangement===\nThe rhombicosidodecahedron shares its [[vertex arrangement]] with three [[nonconvex uniform polyhedra]]: the [[small stellated truncated dodecahedron]], the [[small dodecicosidodecahedron]] (having the triangular and pentagonal faces in common), and the [[small rhombidodecahedron]] (having the square faces in common).\n\nIt also shares its vertex arrangement with the [[Polyhedron compound#Uniform compounds|uniform compounds]] of [[compound of six pentagrammic prisms|six]] or [[compound of twelve pentagrammic prisms|twelve pentagrammic prisms]].\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:400px; vertical-align:top; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n|[[File:Small rhombicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]<br>Rhombicosidodecahedron\n|[[File:Small dodecicosidodecahedron.png|100px]]<br>[[Small dodecicosidodecahedron]]\n|[[File:Small rhombidodecahedron.png|100px]]<br>[[Small rhombidodecahedron]]\n|-\n|[[File:Small stellated truncated dodecahedron.png|100px]]<br>[[Small stellated truncated dodecahedron]]\n|[[File:UC36-6 pentagrammic prisms.png|100px]]<br>[[Compound of six pentagrammic prisms]]\n|[[File:UC37-12 pentagrammic prisms.png|100px]]<br>[[Compound of twelve pentagrammic prisms]]\n|}\n\n== Rhombicosidodecahedral graph ==\n{{Infobox graph\n | name = Rhombicosidodecahedral graph\n | image = [[File:Rhombicosidodecahedral graph.png|240px]]\n | image_caption = Pentagon centered Schlegel diagram\n | namesake = \n | vertices = 60\n | edges = 120\n | automorphisms = 120\n | radius = \n | diameter = \n | girth = \n | chromatic_number =\n | chromatic_index = \n | fractional_chromatic_index = \n | properties = [[Quartic graph]], [[hamiltonian graph|Hamiltonian]], [[regular graph|regular]]\n}}\nIn the [[mathematics|mathematical]] field of [[graph theory]], a '''rhombicosidodecahedral graph''' is the [[1-skeleton|graph of vertices and edges]] of the rhombicosidodecahedron, one of the [[Archimedean solid]]s. It has 60 [[Vertex (graph theory)|vertices]] and 120 edges, and is a [[quartic graph]] [[Archimedean graph]].<ref>{{citation|last1=Read|first1=R. C.|last2=Wilson|first2=R. J.|title=An Atlas of Graphs|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year= 1998|page=269}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rhombicosidodecahedral_graph-squarecenter.png|thumb|left|Square centered [[Schlegel diagram]]]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Truncated rhombicosidodecahedron]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{The Geometrical Foundation of Natural Structure (book)}} (Section 3-9)\n*{{cite book|author=Cromwell, P.|year=1997|title=Polyhedra|location=United Kingdom|publisher=Cambridge|pages=79\u201386 ''Archimedean solids''|isbn=0-521-55432-2}}\n*''[[The Big Bang Theory]] Series 8 Episode 2 - The Junior Professor Solution'': features this solid as the answer to an impromptu science quiz the main four characters have in Leonard and Sheldon's apartment, and is also illustrated in [[Chuck Lorre]]'s '''Vanity Card #461''' at the end of that episode.\n\n==External links==\n*{{mathworld2 |urlname=SmallRhombicosidodecahedron |title=Small Rhombicosidodecahedron |urlname2=ArchimedeanSolid |title2=Archimedean solid}}\n**{{mathworld |urlname=SmallRhombicosidodecahedralGraph |title=Small rhombicosidodecahedron graph}}\n*{{KlitzingPolytopes|polyhedra.htm|3D convex uniform polyhedra|x3o5x - srid}}\n*[http://www.dr-mikes-math-games-for-kids.com/polyhedral-nets.html?&name=Rhombicosidodecahedron#applet Editable printable net of a Rhombicosidodecahedron with interactive 3D view]\n*[http://www.mathconsult.ch/showroom/unipoly/ The Uniform Polyhedra]\n*[http://www.georgehart.com/virtual-polyhedra/vp.html Virtual Reality Polyhedra] The Encyclopedia of Polyhedra\n\n\n{{Archimedean solids}}\n{{Polyhedron navigator}}\n\n[[Category:Uniform polyhedra]]\n[[Category:Archimedean solids]]\n", "name_user": "OfficialURL", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVertex arrangement", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombicosidodecahedron"}
